Aggregating the FRED datasets¶

In [23]:
Int_group = Int.groupby('year')['FederalRate'].mean()
Int_group=Int_group.to_frame().reset_index()

Oil_group=Oil.groupby('year')['CrudeOil'].mean()
Oil_group=Oil_group.reset_index()

Emp_group=Emp.groupby('year')['InsuredUnemployment'].mean()
Emp_group=Emp_group.reset_index()

Net Income (ni) VS Revenue (revt)¶

In [77]:
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn import metrics


#'revt' is independent variable and 'ni' is the dependent variable
X = Fred_Air_merged[['revt']]
y = Fred_Air_merged['ni']

# Splitting the data into training and testing sets
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=0)

# Creating a linear regression model
model = LinearRegression()

# Training the model
model.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Making predictions on the test set
y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

# Plotting the results
plt.scatter(X_test, y_test, color='black')
plt.plot(X_test, y_pred, color='blue', linewidth=3)
plt.xlabel('Revenue (revt)')
plt.ylabel('Net Income (ni)')
plt.title('Revenue vs Net Income Regression')
plt.show()

# Printing the model coefficients
print('Coefficient:', model.coef_[0])
print('Intercept:', model.intercept_)

# Evaluating the model
print('Mean Absolute Error:', metrics.mean_absolute_error(y_test, y_pred))
print('Mean Squared Error:', metrics.mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred))
print('Root Mean Squared Error:', metrics.mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred, squared=False))

Coefficient (0.0757): This represents the estimated change in the dependent variable ('ni' or Net Income) for a one-unit change in the independent variable ('revt' or Revenue). In this case, for every one unit increase in Revenue, Net Income is estimated to increase by approximately 0.0757 units.

Intercept (-83.2525): This is the estimated value of Net Income when Revenue is zero. However, the interpretation might not be meaningful in this context because having zero revenue doesn't make practical sense for a business like this. The intercept is often more relevant in different contexts.

Mean Absolute Error (352.83): This is the average absolute difference between the predicted Net Income and the actual Net Income on the test data. It gives you an idea of the average magnitude of errors in your predictions.

Mean Squared Error (538931.93): This is the average squared difference between the predicted and actual Net Income. It amplifies larger errors, giving you an idea of the overall accuracy of the model.

Root Mean Squared Error (734.12): This is the square root of the Mean Squared Error. It's in the same unit as the dependent variable ('ni' in this case) and provides a more interpretable measure of the model's performance. In your case, it means that, on average, your predictions for Net Income are off by approximately 734.12 units.

Interpreting these metrics involves assessing whether the model is providing satisfactory predictions. A lower Mean Absolute Error and Root Mean Squared Error indicate better model performance. You should also consider the specific characteristics of your data and the context of your analysis to determine if these errors are acceptable for your application. If the errors are too large, you might need to explore more sophisticated models or refine your features.
